  "prompt": "Who discovered Avogadro's number?",
  "response": "Avogadro's number, which is approximately \\(6.022 \\times 10^{23}\\), is named after the Italian scientist Amedeo Avogadro, who proposed the idea that equal volumes of gases, at the same temperature and pressure, have the same number of molecules. However, the actual numerical value of Avogadro's number was not determined until later in the 19th century.\n\nThe value itself was established through the work of several scientists. The chemist Jean Baptiste Perrin is often credited with calculating Avogadro's number around 1909, using various methods including Brownian motion and the determination of the charge of an electron. Although Avogadro himself did not discover the number, his contributions laid the groundwork for understanding the mole concept in chemistry.",
